fields.review: There's something charming about music that could come live from a garage. Not the most memorable album I've ever heard but I can't deny its quality. Nice mix of grunge/clean tones, really enjoy all the layered vocals/two part harmonies and the like. For how many parts there are to this band it seems like their tracks are awfully dense with things to listen to (which I am a big fan of)

I remember everyone going gaga over dream theater back when I frequented the tabcrawler forums in JR high. For some reason I didn't have high expectations for this though I'm not sure if I listened to them before. The John Myung/John Petrucci/Mike Portnoy hype didn't disappoint. These guys are monster musicians and it shows. That was expected (this is what Dream Theater has been billed as from the tabcrawler days) The variance of the tracks surprised me - some sound like the Blind Guardian style speed/ballad/epic metal, other more prog rock, others sound neither (Surrounded, Wait for Sleep) It is a bit hard to pick a best track a few stick out to me for different reasons. It feels like when I appreciate this album most it is when they sound like other bands that I like (Blind Guardian, Yes, Rush).  I can appreciate why people are into Dream Theater for that reason...you kind of get a neat mix of all of the above. The last notable standout is the vocalist. I'm not sure who it is but they have that high pitched Geddy Lee sort of sound that some people (totally understandably) hate. For whatever reason it fits the album perfectly so I'm into it. The last last notable standpoint is the ridiculous guitar solos. Super tropey metal shit, A+
Solid and inoffensive tunes. I like the grooves on here especially for working. The album kind of blends together for me so I have a hard time picking out tracks but it's enjoyable nonetheless.

Had to listen to this a few times over before the appealing parts of it started to stick out. Even then I don't think this is my cup of tea. None of the tracks really hooked me and the timbres are mediocre to OK. To be fair: Do you know anyone who refuses to play old video games cause they can't see past the bad graphics? That's sort of how I am with music...the older the recording technology, the better the other aspects need to be to enjoy it. The recording quality here isn't that bad, but maybe its weak enough that it doesn't sound "rich" in the way that I was expecting something like this to and there weren't any overwhelmingly redeeming qualities. More modern recordings of music in this genre or remasters are far more enjoyable to me - its like the difference between drinking a dark tea with milk (looks the same, but has something missing) vs drinking coffee (thicker and satisfying) I think this is why "Do It Good" sticks out for me as best track - not because its the best song on the album (it isn't a song) but it has the most satisfying sound. I'm Her Daddy has bits of it as well. Ain't No Sunshine is favourite song on the album. Other note - this genre is a welcome change of pace for most of the albums I've listened to so far, so points for that.

It's hard not to have some nostalgia for this album. The sound is classic, which is good because there's not a lot of dynamics across the album. Weirdly I guess this makes this good as an "easy listening" metal album. It is hard to dislike this album. With that being said, I'm surprised I'm ranking it as high as I am cause it isn't anywhere near a personal favourite or anything. Just solid classics
Generally I'm not a huge metal fan but I can get behind this melodic stuff. That being said, it felt a bit on the blander side. Inoffensive. Not super memorable for me

This opening track is RAD - its cheesy and stupid as hell which is right up my alley. The rest of the album is pretty good so I've had a hard time picking my favourite track. Realistically Testarossa Autodrive or Protovision or Deadcruiser are the best music tracks but nothing will top the hype of the cheesy story in prelude for me. In fact, I am a little disappointed this entire album wasnt like...an electronic opera. Still great

Y'know how Im a scrub that generally isn't into old music cause of bad recording quality? Well this is an exception. Maybe it is a remaster or something. This is a fun listen. I can appreciate why people liked to get baked and listen to music like this - it is chill, fun and exciting at different times so there's a bit of a journey for the ear. I appreciate it for the same reason I appreciate something like Black Sabbath even though its a different genre.
All of these rock albums are blending together. They're not bad but they're kind of...indistinct. For this album, nothing really matched the excitement of the first track (even Smoke on the Water)

Nothing here really grabs me. Its kind of 'ho hum' music for me. I don't listen to a lot of Alice in Chains and they seem like one of those "storied bands" . Coupled with what I'm reading off the wikipedia page for Jar of Flies (I've been trying to get into the habit of learning about the story behind the music on top of music itself) I can appreciate this album is sort of a landmark in this bands history. It is supposed to be emotional I guess, but it isn't for me. Maybe I should read the lyrics? I did appreciate the length of the track...Longer albums start to feel more self indulgent, especially when they dont grab me, so I like that they kept this abbreviated. Less is more

Nearly 30 picks in, I did a revisit and I gotta saw this really stands out from anything else in one key regard, it's humanity. It's about real people, it's understated and it's incredibly touching. It is and it has soul.

Not a bad album, 7th looks bad now, but it'll float up later. It doesn't do enough to differentiate itself from a lot of the other synthwave out there. Nightcall is the only track that feels like a standout. And the end of the day, I said to myself which would I rather listen to, Nightcall or Parallel Play.

I think this is a really solid album. It's held back a bit by the production of the era and the fact that they were pretty early into the hard rock game. This is a pretty wicked power trio album when you consider it. I never really considered how much Bruce set the stage for later power trio bass/vocalists like Geddy Lee, Phil Lynott and Greg Lake. Clapton's guitar work would stand up even today.

Home to a couple hard hitters. I wasn't only partial to the biggies though, I almost went with Never Before as my top track. I was really digging the potential of the space trucking profession after this listen though.
It kinda confirmed that grunge really isn't the sound for me, but at the same time I was pretty impressed by large chunks of it. Not for me, but expectations exceeded.
solid album. nothing really stood out, but nothing disappointed either
this band can get a bit weird sometimes. I have to be in the right mood to enjoy them
This album was surprisingly consistent. not my usual, but great when grinding through a bunch of code
This album just didn't have the energy to keep me interested
Solid album. Not a bad song on it. It was tough deciding which song I liked best.
This band surprised me with how good they are, however I felt the album was a little too tame for my liking
The album started off great, but was really inconsistent. Lots of highs, but also lots of lows
I was expecting a more consistently awesome album from cream. This has some great songs, but also a lot that are just meh.

I got really excited when I saw the song list and this album did not disappoint! the only reason this album isn't no. 1 is because of the organ. Organ music can work, and while deep purple did it well, they didn't do it good enough. I also had a hard time choosing between Lazy and Peace Trucking
I low expectations going and I was still disappointed. The slow pace and flat key signature made it hard for me to care.
I certainly did not come into this not knowing what to expect from Sloan, but I did find myself attempting to sing along more than I expected (which would have worked better if I knew the lyrics).

This came in pretty much as expected for prog metal, I would say. Pull Me Under was giving me shades of some Metallica at the outset, so I was pulled in that direction. Aditi struggled greatly through the whole thing.
Audio, Video, Disco felt to me like where I wanted the album to end; Phanisphere felt like something I would have wanted more in the middle of the album.

I usually prefer higher-energy music. But here, for the most part, Bill seems to pack a punch with each track and then keep moving before I found myself in a lull. I did have to pull myself through In My Heart. Also, I did read the album cover; thanks for asking.
I enjoyed a lot of the sounds on here. Suburbia was unexpected for a French electronica experience. In fact, there was more English than I was expecting generally.
how this guy's vocal cords must feel after doing this.

Some pretty good highs here. Some of the inbetween left me just waiting for the next high. Obviously, Smoke on the Water is one of the first songs your teenage garage band learned. At least, we sure did. Pretty timeless.

Not particularly offended by anything, but also not particularly excited by anything. Cleaner than what I was expecting for an album listed as "grunge", but also more controlled than I was expecting. This one was a tough one. I had to spend some time with it to sort out how I feel. My opinion improved on subsequent listens. I don’t even know what to say about Swing On This. It felt very experimental to me.
There are a few duds here that drive down its overall ranking but the highs are high, baby. Definitely a classic soul album

Every time I hear this album I'm blown away. The mix of the OG stoner metal sound and the strong grasp of classic blues melodies are astounding, but the fact that it came out in 1970 is just crazy to me. A band could release this today and it wouldn't sound too out of place. Also this is probably Sabbath's 4th best album. wtf. GOAT.

It's very hard for me to seperate Opeth's clean albums from their classic prog/death works. But this one certainly stands up on its own, even as part of a double album. It does lose something toward the end however.
Nothing groundbreaking but certainly entertaining. My favourite of the sythwave revival movement of the 2010's

my ranking here is low which is mostly a function of the strength of the other choices. this is a good album; one I've been meaning to listen to for years. Reasonably psych-y, kind of blues-y, very reminiscent of the period. Bruce sounds equally Bowie and Homme at points. my ranking may change on this given further listens
a blast from my high school past, this is a classic. I do think it gets too drawn out at points however.
I'm not sure there's a better EP out there for me. This is the way I prefer AiC; stripped down and (largely) acoustic. Strong melodies, lyrical content and atmosphere make this AiC's strongest work.

This album wasn't awful, but it wasn't super memorable either.  Lots of soft-pop-rock Beatles influenced songs, although there were some standouts.  'Burn for It' was super catchy, and I also liked 'Down in the Basement' which reminded me of Bob Dylan in the both the music and especially the vocals.  I prefer my rock music with a bit more energy and power, and outside of a few songs, this album just didn't bring that. 4/10

I would rank this album much higher if I wasn't comparing it against other Dream Theater albums, but Dream Theater sets a high bar.  The difference is this album is a little more rambley and less refined vs some later albums.  'Pull Me Under' is a stellar song, easily the album's best.  Any song in which James LaBrie sings for excessive duration in a ballady voice is the worst. 7/10

Band has some cool beats, but right when you start to get into it, there's some unneccessary pause or sound effect.  I feel like these guys would be better served to stick to more traditional song structures, too many of the songs feel like a collection of cool sounds, rather than a cohesive song.  That said there are some high points, New Lands is great, and the chorus on Civilization is oh-so catchy.  4/10

A little too slow and boring for me.  Would be good background music for sitting on the couch reading a book, but not something I'd listen to for the sake of listening. 'Ain't No Sunshine' was brilliant however, so moody and soulful.  'Better Off Dead' is good too, but the rest of album doesn't match-up.  4/10

If you think of this as a metal album you might be a little underwhelmed, but if you think of it as a blues album it's fantastic. Ozzy is far from the world's best singer, but his voice fits the music so well. 7.5/10

This album really spoke to me as an angst-ridden teenager, and considering how beautifully done it is, I'm a little ashamed to admit that I haven't listened to it in quite some time.  Michael Akerfelt is an incredible vocalist, I can't think of anyone else who has both a beautiful soft singing voice plus a perfect metal growl.  And to me, that is when Opeth are at their best - when they do what few others can pull-off and seamlessly combine both soft and hard elements on the same album (eg Blackwater Park).  7/10

I actually like their sound, its very futuristic/industrial, but it seemed like every song started out really cool and then fizzled out halfway through.  What ever happened to building up to a climax throughout the song.  Wifey: "I can't believe I sat through this whole thing.  I should have brought my earplugs down". 3/10

Some timeless classics on this album, but some mundane stuff too.  It's not as unique, and therefore hasn't aged as well, as some other albums from that era (SgtPepper, The Doors etc).  Wifey: "If I didn't know that you were doing an album ranking thing, I would think your taste in music has gotten way worse lately."  5/10
This album starts out strong, and doesn't let up.  Timeless blend of blues and proto-metal that I could listen to over and over. 8/10
Nirvana proved that not only does grunge not always suck, it can actually be pretty good.  Unfortunately this album does not follow suit. Hard to pick a favorite.  3/10
